What I Say to My Non-American Friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad and my foreign friends always ask, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is actually happening in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
First of all, be careful not to misinterpret the 2016 elections.
Contrary to some comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump has tapped into the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet Trump failed to win the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the election by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If hundreds of thousands of votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
That said, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rising social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest best-seller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the large difference between California and the Appalachians.
Research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income whites without university degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically occupied the lower end of inequality.
In 1999, the mortality rates among whites without higher education were about 30% lower than those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
Furthermore, employment in industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for white working-class people, has significantly declined over the last generation, to just 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters have been lured by Trump's promises to make things move and bring jobs back to the industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may well make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you shouldn't underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous disdain for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality television, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize the attention of television viewers, and that the best way to do this is to make extreme statements, without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What irritates commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his self-centered permanent campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that deters some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves toward the political center in order to attract more support.
This is what George W. Bush successfully did in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, claims he won the popular vote and by acting as if it were really the case, he pleases his base voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist appointments at the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and for the Department of Health and Human Services are at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he intends to satisfy both camps at the same time.
Fourthly, one must not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends speak as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
Despite their many problems, the United States are not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' objective was not to ensure that the government be harmonious, but to limit political power through a system of checks and balances that makes the exercise of these powers difficult.
A joke about this says that the founders created a political system so that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or for anyone else.
Inefficiency has been put at the service of freedom.
Trump's presidency is still in its early stages, and we cannot be certain of what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have safeguarded this balance of powers within the administration, as Madison wished.
And the permanent officials of the executive branch still carry significant weight.
Finally, my friends are wondering what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Honestly, I don't know, but I worry less about the rise of China than about that of Trump.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing major global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under U.S. leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can be certain that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first candidate from a major party in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's statements and those of his members suggest that he may continue to do so.
After all, the coercive and persuasive power of the United States largely comes from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
The director of Trump's Budget speaks of a budget of coercive power, with budget cuts made to the Department of State and the United Nations system.
Other government members are advocating replacing multilateral trade agreements with bilateral arrangements that are "fair and balanced." Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to be able to reassure them on these issues.
But I can't.
